Ã¡n Leyva brothers, who were formerly aligned with the Sinaloa Cartel, are now allies of Los Zetas', '                           On 6 March 2008, Bout was arrested in Thailand on terrorism charges by the Royal Thai Police in cooperation with American authorities, and the United States ambassador requested his extradition under the Extradition Act with Thailand, which was eventually mandated by the Thai High Court in August 2010. Bout was accused of intending to smuggle arms to the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC)\r\n for use against U.S. forces in Colombia, but denied his charges and predicted an acquittal.', '                           On 2 November 2011, Bout was convicted by a jury in a Manhattan federal court of conspiracy to kill U.S. citizens and officials, delivery of anti-aircraft missiles, and providing aid to a terrorist organization, and was sentenced to 25 years\' imprisonment. Since June 2012, Bout has been held at the United States Penitentiary, Marion.', '                            He was designated as a global terrorist in 2003 by India and the United States with a reward of US$25 million for his capture for his believed role in the 1993 Bombay bombings. In 2011, he was named number three on \"The World\'s 10 Most Wanted Fugitives\" by the FBI and Forbes. Dawood is widely believed to have masterminded the March 1993 bombings in Bombay. In 2003, the Indian and United States governments declared him a \"Global Terrorist.\" The Indian Deputy Prime Minister, Lal Krishna Advani described it as a major development.', '                             Ibrahim is currently on India\'s \"Most Wanted List\".In public discourse in June 2017, Ram Jethmalani confirmed that after the Bombay blasts, Dawood Ibrahim had called him from London, saying that he was prepared to come to India and stand trial, on the condition that he should not be subjected to any third-degree treatment from the police.\r\n Jethmalani had conveyed this to Sharad Pawar, but the politicians in power did not agree to this proposal. As per Jethmalani, their refusal to allow Dawood\'s return was due to their fears that he would expose their secrets', '                           Carillo was the nephew of Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo, also known as \"Don Neto\", the Guadalajara Cartel leader. Amado got his start in the drug business under the tutelage of his uncle Ernesto and later brought in his brothers. Carrillo\'s father died in April 1986. Carillo\'s brother, Cipriano Carrillo Fuentes, died in 1989 under mysterious circumstances.\r\n', '                          Initially, Carrillo was part of the Guadalajara Cartel, sent to Ojinaga, Chihuahua to oversee the cocaine shipments of his uncle,  Carrillo worked with Pablo Escobar and the Cali Cartel smuggling drugs from Colombia to Mexico and The United States. He also worked with \"El Chapo\" (Joaquin Guzman Loera), the Arellano Felix family, and the Beltran Leyva organization. During his tenure, Carrillo reportedly built a multibillion-dollar drug empire. It was estimated that he may have made over $25 billion in revenue over the course of his career.'),
